Dean. robinson resigns: students ask why! The statement read in part, "I have decided to resign the position of Dean of Students at Iowa State. . . ." It was signed Eugene Robin- son. Dr. Robinson, his associates, and his advisors deal with all policies that involve Iowa State students. When Dean Robinson resigned, the student body acted with concern. This reaction showed that the line of communication Dr. Robinson and his staff has developed between students and administration was and is definite- ly open. Dean of Students Eugene Robinson residence department fills parental role Director of Residence Charles Frederiksen has a huge family to care for. Mr. Frederiksen and his residence staff must take care of 8,000 resi- dence hall students and 1,300 married student families. The twelve member staff has to house, feed, and generally manage a majority of the student population. And like loving parents they take care of all money matters while keeping an eye on us through student government and Head Resident programming. It's common belief that the yearbook staff article is a sob story telling how little appreciated and rewarded the staff is. Well, this year we aren't going to tell you that we slaved long hours over this work of art; we aren't going to tell you that we sacrificed our pleasures to finish this book; No, we aren't going to tell you that we worked above ourselves at times to compile this history of ISU. But, we are going to tell you that we appreciate the work of everyone who made this book possible and hope you appreciate it as much. The staff stayed on the good side of these shrewd business- men, business manager Dick Johnson and assistant business manager Greg Cornwell as they helped issue the paychecks. Three people who examine their work for unity are copy editor Doug Anderson, layout editor Ann Furnam, and art editor Denise Lambert. 10 When you notice your name in the index and take a look at the senior listings, remember seniors editor Ellen Seeck and index editors Mary Ellen Porter and Lyn Steinke. Four people we couldn't have done without are managing editor Christie McKinley, sports editors Bruce Fritz and Kurt Magnusson, and managing photo editor Jane Whicher. Tom Dunkar (left) and Duane Card are preparing a page reproduction for the offset camera located in Jefferson, Iowa, 40 miles from the backshop. The Daily's stand on the use of four-letter words winter quarter highlighted Greg Lauser's tenure in office and created a statewide sc--del. Lauser chose to spell out all expletives used by persons at public meetings when they were the central issue of a news story. He subsequently had spelled out for him various and sundry reasons why these words weren't acceptable in print. Despite this dubious highlight the Daily pro- vided coverage of the menagerie of events taking place throughout the year at the Moo U. Zoo. Among the strangest animals to visit the campus this year was a precedent-setting student demon- stration supporting the University's dean of stu- dents. Normally the object of students' scorn, the dean of students at Iowa State became a martyr of academic freedom at the hands of protestors led by "straight" man Dennis Forsyth, GSB President. The Daily came through with a typically intelligent question, "WHY?" Overall it was a year of change for the Daily. The journalism department must have seen the "Good Ship Lollipop" going down for the third time because it pulled all its troops, alias 222 reporters, off the boat. The "Lollipop" may now assume the role of an all-day "sucker." In an attempt to avoid a sellout to any local candy manufacturers, the ship changed helms- meny this spring. This last spring Kent Baker took over with every intention of reforming the Daily's image as "The Flying Dutchman" — or everybody's nightmare. With the exit of 222ers from the staff. Baker is left in midstream without anyone to paddle; but we have every confidence he will carry on admirably. Bellett 29 ocean cruises for nrotc The purpose of the Naval Reserve Officer Training Corps is to train men to become qualified officers in the Navy or Marine Corps. This is accomplished through instruction in essential military subjects, education received from the University, and exposure to the military way of life and social customs. Each midshipman completes one or several "summer cruises" in which he experiences, first hand, the life of an officer. The cruise areas span the oceans from Viet Nam to the Mediterranean Activities centered around the Uni- versity community are also important. Midshipmen are active in everything from Navy intramural, to the Drill team, to the Order of the Sextant, which sponsored this year's social highlight, "Blue Lagoon."
